l name referring to a house named with this word.","Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): variant of   Abt  , a habitational name from Opatów in Poland."]},{"name":"Apter","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Avrohom, Bronya, Eliezer, Naftali.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): habitational name for someone from Apt (see   Apt  ).","English: habitational name from Aptor in Marldon, Devon, composed of Old English <i>uppe</i> ‘up, above’ + <i>torr</i> ‘rocky outcrop’."]}]},{"name":"Eynion","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Welsh: from <i>Enniaun</i>, an old Welsh personal name ultimately derived from Late Latin <i>Annianus</i>, but also associated with Welsh <i>einion</i> ‘anvil’, taken as implying stability and fortitude. See also   Beynon   and compare   Onion  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Beynon","meanings":["Welsh (southern): variant of   Bennion  ."]},{"name":"Hennion","meanings":["Welsh: from a hypercorrected form of the Welsh personal name <i>Ennion</i>, see   Eynon  .","Flemish and French (mainly Nord): from a pet form of the personal name   Henri   or <i>Jehen</i> (see   Jean  )."]},{"name":"Bennion","meanings":["Welsh: Anglicized form of Welsh <i>ap Einion</i>, <i>ap Eynon</i> ‘son of <i>Einion</i>’ (see   Eynon  )."]},{"name":"Binion","meanings":["Welsh: Anglicized form of Welsh <i>ap Einion</i>, <i>ap Eynon</i> ‘son of <i>Einion</i>’. See   Eynon   and compare   Bennion  . This form of the surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Kenyon","meanings":["English (Lancashire): habitational name from a place near Warrington, which is of uncertain etymology. There was formerly an ancient burial mound there and Ekwall has speculated that the name is a shortened form of a British name composed of the elements <i>crūc</i> ‘mound’ + a personal name cognate with Welsh <i>Einion</i> (see   Eynon  ).","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Coinín</b> ‘son of <i>Coinín</i>’, a byname based on a diminutive of <i>cano</i> ‘wolf’, also Anglicized as   Canning   and   Cunneen  . The similarity to the borrowed word <i>coinín</i> ‘coney, rabbit’ has sometimes caused this name to be Anglicized as   Rabbitt  .","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Fhinghin</b>, ‘son of Finghen’, a personal name meaning ‘fair-born’."]}]},{"name":"Ralph","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Ralf","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Ralph ap Eynion of Malpas was born about 1125, in Malpas, Cheshire, England, his father, Nigel De Puis, was 27 and his mother, Agnes de Malpas, was 16. He had at least 2 sons and 4 daughters with Beatrix de Gernon. He died in 1200, in his hometown, at the age of 76."},"et":{"about 1125–1200":"umbes 1125–1200","1125–1200":"1125–1200","1130–Male":"1130–Surnud","1133–Male":"1133–Surnud","1145–Male":"1145–Surnud","1135–1175":"1135–1175","1150–Female":"1150–Surnud","1150–Male":"1150–Surnud","1154–Male":"1154–Surnud","1155–Female":"1155–Surnud","1160–Female":"1160–Surnud","1100–Male":"1100–Surnud","1110–Female":"1110–Surnud","about 1150":"umbes 1150","1154":"1154","1110":"1110","1175":"1175","1130":"1130","1150":"1150","1160":"1160","1125":"1125","1135":"1135","1200":"1200","1145":"1145","1100":"1100","1155":"1155","1133":"1133","about 1125":"umbes 1125","Abt 1160":"umbes 1160","about 1155":"umbes 1155","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Malpas, Cheshire, England